t me give one example. One day Sri Ramakrishna was sitting in his room =\r\naround evening when he saw a vision of Lord Krishna with another young boy,=\r\n dressed like a cowherd, standing in the middle of a lotus.&nbsp; The next =\r\nday he saw the exact same boy come to Dakshineshwar. Incidentally the boy&#39;s=\r\n name was Rakhal, meaning cowherd. Sri Ramakrishna told him that he was in =\r\na previous birth, one of the cowherd companions of Sri Krishna in\n Vrndavan=\r\na! Later, many decades later, when Sri Ramakrishna himself had left his phy=\r\nsical body, Rakhal went on to become a teriffic saint of very very high cal=\r\niber named Swami Brahmananda and one of the greatest devotees of Lord Krshn=\r\na. His spiritual fulfillment came through worship of Lord Krshna and the st=\r\nudy of the Gita. In his last years, he would see and interact with Krshna a=\r\nt all times and hours before his own death he saw Lord Krshna come to him a=\r\nnd take his hand and call him back to his own realm. Within hours of this e=\r\nxperience he died. The point being, the vision that Sri Ramakrishna saw man=\r\ny decades ago,at a time when Rakhal himself had no clue of his potential an=\r\nd his specific path, all proved correct and accurate. Ramakrishna himself w=\r\nas not alive to see that day,&nbsp;therefore it cannot be said e had any ag=\r\nenda in making those proclamations to Rakhal about his past life and his pa=\r\nth. So if all this turned out to be true in such a\n tremendous manner, we h=\r\nave no basis to say that his declaratoin of Rakhal&#39;s, or anyone else&#39;s&nbsp=\r\n;past life was not-true. &lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;DIV style=3D&quot;RIGHT: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;/=\r\nDIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV style=3D&quot;RIGHT: auto&quot;&gt;&nbsp;Wwe know what imagination and visuali=\r\nzation is. All of us have these powers of imagination is various measures. =\r\nBut none of us can &#39;imagine&#39; the future and make it happen the way we imagi=\r\nne i